-------------------- File Permissions -----------------------
File Permissions:- File permissions in Ubuntu/Linux control who can access a file or folder and what actions they can perform.
------Permission Groups---------
Ubuntu divides users into 3 groups:
    Group	    Meaning
     u	     User/Owner
     g	       Group
     o	      Others
Default Permission  Ex:- -rwx/rw-/r--
rwx = user = U 
rw- = group = G
r-- = other = O
Here, We can change change Permission in two way,
a) Symbolic ( rwx )
b) Numeric  ( 777 )

------Symbolic Permissions----
Symbol   	  Meaning       	Action
  r       	 Read	      View file content
  w	         Write      Edit or modify file
  x	         Execute	  Run file as program/script
1. chmod o = wx file name/ directory = Change write or execute permission on others in perticuler file/ directory
2. chmod g + r file mame / directory = Add the read permission  to the group in the perticuler file 
3. chmod u - wx file name / directory = Remove the write or execute permission permission to user in the  perticuler file 

--------- Numeric Permission -----------------
Symbol        Number         Meaning        Action
  r             4              Read      View the file content 
  w             2              Write     View and write in the file 
  x             1              Execute   Execute the file 
Default Ex:- rxw rwx rwx file name = ( 777)
user = 7, group = 7, other = 7

-----Add numbers together----------
Permission	    Value
 rwx	             7
 rw-	             6
 r-x	             5
 r--              	4

1. chmod 777 file name = Highest permission ( read, write, execute ) to all of them
2. chmod 400 file name = User have only read permission 

The umask removes permissions from the default permissions:

Files start with 666 (rw-rw-rw-)
Directories start with 777 (rwxrwxrwx)

steps, Check the current umask
umask 
in a symbolic form 
umask -S

Change umask temporarily
This affects only the current shell session:
umask 022
Examples:

022 → New files: 644, directories: 755
027 → New files: 640, directories: 750
077 → New files: 600, directories: 700

Change umask permanently for a user
Add the desired umask to the user's shell startup file:

nano ~/.bashrc
Add:

umask 022

Save and reload:

source ~/.bashrc

Alternatively, for login shells:

nano ~/.profile

Add:

umask 022

Log out and back in for it to take effect.

